    <article class="section">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="article-body">
          
          <p>
            A restless stretch of the West Coast has been rumbling beneath the surface, with recent earthquakes in Oregon and California reminding residents that the ground here never truly sleeps. From the Oregon coast to the Bay Area, the seismic chatter has been small in scale but sharp enough to keep attention fixed on the faults below.
          </p>

          <p>
            On Saturday afternoon, a magnitude 4.2 earthquake struck in the Pacific Ocean off Oregon, about 430 miles west of Yachats and Newport, at a depth of about six miles. <em>KATU</em> reported that the quake occurred on the Blanco Fracture Zone, and no tsunami or damage was expected. Oregon has also seen a steady stream of smaller recent earthquakes, including a 2.1 near Sandy, a 2.0 near Ashland, and a 2.1 near Port Orford, while <em>Earthquake Track</em> lists 10 quakes in Oregon in the past seven days and 33 in the past 30 days.
          </p>

          <p>
            In California, <em>ABC7</em> reported a San Francisco earthquake that began as a preliminary magnitude 3.0 near the San Francisco Zoo before being downgraded to 2.9, followed by aftershocks of 2.0 and 2.7 just minutes later. All three were centered two miles south southwest of the zoo, and no injuries or major damage were reported.
          </p>

          <p>
            As the dust settles on these recent Oregon and California earthquakes, one thing remains clear: the wild West Coast is alive with untamed energy, a rugged reminder for every explorer to respect the raw power beneath our boots. Whether you're hiking the Oregon coast trails near Yachats or chasing sunsets in the Bay Area, these shakes are nature's call to stay alert and adventure ready. Dive deeper into the seismic pulse of our backyard faults, and let the ground's whispers fuel your next bold trek.
          </p>

